\c 1 
\rem Childrens
\s Nebuchadnezzar’s court

\p \v 1 [oeb:In the third year of the reign of King Jehoiakim of Judah, Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon laid siege to Jerusalem. |:]

\p \v 2 [oeb:The \nd Lord\nd* handed King Jehoiakim over to him, with some of the vessels of the house of God; and he carried them off to the land of Shinar to the temple of his god, and placed them in the temple treasury. |:]

\p \v 3 [oeb:The king|:Nebuchadnezzar, the king of Babylon,] commanded Ashpenaz, the chief of his [oeb:eunuchs|:servants], to bring to him [oeb:some|:certain] of the Israelite[oeb:|:s and some of their] princes and nobles. \v 4 They were to be young men who were [oeb:without physical defect|:strong] and handsome, [oeb:comfortable with all types of knowledge,|:] well taught and quick to learn and able to serve in the king’s palace. [oeb:T|:And t]hey were to be taught the learning and the language of the Chaldeans. \v 5 The king gave to them each day some of his rich food and some of the wine which he drank. \v 6 He also commanded that they should be taught for three years, and that at the end of that time they should enter the royal service.

\p \v 6 Among these young men were: Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah[oeb:, all of whom were from the tribe of Judah|:]; \v 7 but the chief of the king’s [oeb:eunuchs|:servants] gave other names to them. To Daniel he gave the name Belteshazzar, and to Hananiah, Shadrach, and to Mishael, Meshach, and to Azariah, Abednego.

\p \v 8 But Daniel made up his mind not to [oeb:become ritually unclean by being contaminated by|:injure himself with] the rich food of the king nor with the wine which he drank. So he asked the chief of the king’s [oeb:eunuchs|:servants] [oeb:to help him avoid it|:not to make him injure himself]. \v 9 [oeb:G|:And G]od helped Daniel to win the kindness and favor of the chief[oeb:|:of the king’s servants].

\p \v 10 But the chief of the [oeb:eunuchs|:king’s servants] said to Daniel, “I fear that my lord, the king, who has given you your food and your drink, will see that your faces are sadder than those of young men who are your own age, and so you will endanger my head with the king.”

\p \v 11 [oeb:So |:]Daniel [oeb:went|:said] to the guardian whom the chief of the [oeb:eunuchs|:king’s servants] had put over Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah, [oeb:and said|:] \v 12 “[oeb:Test|:Try] [oeb:us|:your servants] [oeb:for|:] ten days; and let us have vegetables to eat and water to drink. \v 13 Then compare the way we look with that of the young men who eat of the king’s rich food. Then do to us as seems best.” \v 14 So he did as they asked and [oeb:tested|:tried] them [oeb:for|:] ten days. \v 15 At the end of ten days they looked better and they were [oeb:healthier|:fatter] than all the young men who ate [oeb:|:of] the king’s rich food. \v 16 So the guardian took away their rich food and the wine and gave them vegetables.

\p \v 17 To these four young men God gave knowledge, learning, and wisdom; and Daniel understood all kinds of visions and dreams.
\p \v 18 [oeb:On the date|:At the end of the days] which the king had fixed for [oeb:introducing|:bringing] [oeb:all the young men|:them] [oeb:to the court|:in], the chief of his [oeb:eunuchs|:servants] brought them [oeb:|:in]to Nebuchadnezzar, \v 19 and the king talked with them. But not one of all the young men was found equal to Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah. So they began to serve the king. \v 20 On every subject which called for wisdom and understanding and about which the king questioned them, he found them ten times better than all the wise men and magicians who were in his entire kingdom.

\p \v 21 [oeb:Daniel remained at the court until the start of the reign of King Cyrus.|:]

\c 2 
\rem Childrens
\s A king’s strange dream

\p \v 1 Nebuchadnezzar in the second year of his reign had dreams, and his mind was so troubled that he could not sleep. \v 2 Then the king sent for the magicians and the wise men, and [oeb:the Chaldaens (|:those]who studied the stars[oeb:)|:] to tell him what his dreams meant. So they came in before the king, \v 3 and he said to them, “I have had a dream and my mind is troubled, for I want to know what the dream means.”

\p \v 4 Then those who studied the stars said to the king [oeb:in Aramaic|:]: “O king, live forever! Tell the dream to your servants and we will tell you what it means.” \v 5 The king answered, “What I now say is certain: if you do not tell me the dream and what it means, you [oeb:will|:shall] be torn limb from limb and your houses [oeb:will|:shall] be made[oeb:ruins|: ash-heaps]. \v 6 But if you tell the dream and what it means, you [oeb:will|:shall] receive from me gifts and rewards and great honors; therefore tell me the dream and what it means.” \v 7 They answered the second time, “Let the king tell the dream to his servants, and we will tell what it means.” \v 8 The king replied, “I see clearly that you wish to gain time, for you know that what I have said is certain, \v 9 and that if you do not tell the dream to me, you will all suffer the same punishment. So you have planned to speak lying and false words before me, until the time when it is to happen has passed. Therefore tell me the dream, and I [oeb:will|:shall] know that you can tell me what it means.” \v 10 The Chaldeans answered the king, “There is no man on earth who can do what the king asks, for no king, however great and powerful, has ever asked such a thing of any wise man or magician, or of one who studies the stars. \v 11 What the king asks is too hard. There is no one else who can tell it to the king, except the gods, who do not live [oeb:among mortals|:with men].” \v 12 This made the king very angry and he ordered all the wise men of Babylon put to death.

\p \v 13 So the command was given that the wise men were to be put to death. [oeb:S|:And s]earch was made for Daniel and his friends that they too might be put to death. \v 14 Then Daniel [oeb:approached|:spoke wisely, to] Arioch, the captain of the king’s guard, who had gone out to put the wise men of Babylon to death, and [oeb:quietly and carefully asked,|:said] \v 15 “Why is the king’s command so harsh?” When Arioch told Daniel the facts, \v 16 he went to the king and asked that he give him time to tell what the dream meant.

\p \v 17 Then Daniel went to his house and told the facts to his friends, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah, [oeb:so|:] that they might [oeb:beg|:ask] the God of heaven to be kind to them and to tell Daniel this secret, so that they might not die with the rest of the wise men of Babylon. \v 19 Then the secret was told to Daniel in a vision at night, and he praised the God of heaven and said:

