\p \v 24 Then Daniel went to Arioch, whom the king had commanded to kill the wise men of Babylon, and said to him, “Do not kill the wise men of Babylon. Take me to the king, and I will tell him what his dream means.”

\p \v 25 Then Arioch quickly brought Daniel to the king and said to him, “I have found a man among the captives from Judah who will tell you what this dream means.” \v 26 The king said to Daniel (whose name was Belteshazzar), “Can you make known to me the dream which I have had and what it means?” \v 27 Daniel answered, “The secret which the king asks is something that neither wise men, magicians, nor those who study the stars can make known to him; \v 28 but there is a God in heaven who tells secrets, and he has made known to King Nebuchadnezzar what [oeb:will|:shall] come in the future. Your dream and the visions which you had as you lay asleep are these: 

\p \v 29 [“The thoughts which came into your mind on your bed concerned what will happen in the future. The one who reveals secrets has made known to you what will come to pass. \v 30 This secret was not revealed to me because I am wiser than other living people, but so that the king might learn the interpretation: so that you might understand the thoughts that have come to you.]

\p \v 31 “You, O king, had a vision and saw a great image. That image was large and it was exceedingly bright as it stood before you, and its appearance was [oeb:terrifying|:terrible]. \v 32 The head of the image was of fine gold, its breast and its arms of silver, its body and its thighs of [oeb:bronze|:brass], \v 33 its legs of iron, its feet part of iron and part of clay. \v 34 You looked at it until a stone was cut out, not by [oeb:human|:the] hands[oeb:|:of men], which struck the image on its feet of iron and clay and broke them in pieces. \v 35 Then the iron, the clay, the [oeb:bronze|:brass], the silver, and the gold were all broken in pieces and became like the chaff which blows from the summer threshing-floors, and the wind carried them away so that nothing was left of them. But the stone that struck the image became a great mountain and filled the earth.

\p \v 36 “This is the dream, and we will tell the king what it means: \v 37 O king, you are the king of kings to whom [oeb:the|:] God [oeb:of heaven|:] has given the rule, the power, the strength, and the glory. \v 38 Over the whole world he has given into your power, [oeb:people|:men], the wild beasts and the birds, and has made you rule over them all. You are the head of gold.

\p \v 39 “After you [oeb:will|:shall] rise another kingdom not so strong as you are, and a third kingdom of [oeb:bronze|:brass], which [oeb:will|:shall] rule over the whole earth. \v 40 A fourth kingdom [oeb:will|:shall] be strong as iron, for iron breaks in pieces and shatters all things, and like iron which crushes, it [oeb:will|:shall] break in pieces and crush all things. \v 41 As you saw the feet and toes, part clay and part iron, it [oeb:will|:shall] be a divided kingdom; but there [oeb:will|:shall] be in it some of the strength of the iron, for you saw the iron mixed with clay. \v 42 As the toes of the feet were part iron and part clay, so the kingdom [oeb:will|:shall] be partly strong and partly broken. \v 43 You saw the iron mixed with clay, for the [oeb:ruling families|:rulers] will [oeb:arrange marriage alliances between each other|:marry one another], but they will not stick together, [oeb:just|:even] as iron does not stick to clay.

\p \v 44 “During the reigns of these kings the God of heaven will set up a kingdom which [oeb:will|:shall] never be destroyed, nor [oeb:will|:shall] the power be left to another people; but it [oeb:will|:shall] break in pieces and destroy all these kingdoms, and it [oeb:will|:shall] stand forever. \v 45 This is shown by the fact that you saw a stone cut out of the mountain, but not with [oeb:human|:the] hands<>. [oeb:I|:And i]t broke in pieces the iron, the [oeb:bronze|:brass], the clay, the silver, and the gold.

\p “The great God has made known to the king what is to come, and the dream is real and this meaning true.”

\p \v 46 Then King Nebuchadnezzar fell upon his face and worshipped Daniel, and ordered that a sacrifice and sweet odors should be offered to him. \v 47 The king also said to Daniel, “Your God is the God of gods and the Lord of kings, and one who tells his secrets to his servant, for you have been able to tell this great secret.” \v 48 Then the king gave Daniel a high position and many costly gifts, and made him ruler over [oeb:the whole province|:all] of Babylon and chief over all the wise men in Babylon. \v 49 [oeb:But|:And] at Daniel’s request the king placed Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego in charge of the province of Babylon; [oeb:while|:but] Daniel stayed in the king’s court.

\c 3 
\rem Childrens
\s The test by fire

\p \v 1 Nebuchadnezzar, the king, made [oeb:a statue|:an image] of gold ninety feet high and nine feet wide. He set it up in the plain of Dura, in the province of Babylon. \v 2 Then he sent for the officers, the governors, the judges, the treasurers, and all the rulers of the provinces [oeb:to attend the dedication of the statue he had set up|:]. \v 3 So [oeb:the officers, the governors, the judges, the treasurers, and all the rulers of the provinces|:] [oeb:|:they] all came together [oeb:for the dedication|:] and stood before the [oeb:statue|:image] that Nebuchadnezzar had set up.

\p \v 4 Then the herald cried aloud, “To you it is commanded, [oeb:|:O] peoples, nations: \v 4 The moment you hear the sound of the [oeb:horn|:trumpet], [oeb:pipe|:flute], [oeb:lyre|:lute], [oeb:trigon|:harp], [oeb:harp, drum|:bagpipe], and [oeb:entire|:all] [oeb:|:kinds ][oeb:|:of ]musical [oeb:ensemble|:instruments], you [oeb:must|:shall] fall down and worship the golden [oeb:statue which King Nebuchadnezzar has set up|:image]. \v 6 Whoever does not fall down and worship [oeb:will|:shall] be thrown into a burning, fiery furnace.” \v 7 So when all the people heard the sound of the [oeb:horn, pipe, lyre, trigon, harp, drum, and entire musical ensemble|:][oeb:|:trumpet, flute, lute, harp, bagpipe, and all kinds of musical instruments], all the peoples, nations, and [oeb:the speakers of all languages|:races] fell down and worshipped the golden [oeb:statue|:image] that King Nebuchadnezzar had set up.

\p \v 8 But at that time certain Chaldeans came near to the king and made this [oeb:accusation|:charge] against the Jews: \v 9 “O king, live forever! O king, you have commanded that every man who hears the sound of the [oeb:horn, pipe, lyre, trigon, harp, drum, and entire musical ensemble must|:trumpet, flute, lute, harp, bagpipe, and all kinds of musical instruments shall] fall down and worship the golden [oeb:statue|:image], \v 11 and that whoever does not fall down and worship [oeb:will|:shall] be thrown into a burning, fiery furnace. \v 12 There are certain Jews, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, whom you have placed in charge of the province of Babylon. These men, O king, have not obeyed your command; they do not serve your gods nor worship the golden [oeb:statue|:image] which you have set up.”

\p \v 13 Then Nebuchadnezzar in his rage and fury gave command to bring in Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego. \v 14 When they were brought before the king, Nebuchadnezzar said to them, “Is it true, [oeb:|:O ]Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, that you do not serve my god nor worship the golden [oeb:statue|:image] which I have set up? \v 15 If you are now ready, as soon as you hear the sound of the [oeb:horn, pipe, lyre, trigon, harp, drum, and entire musical ensemble|:][oeb:|:trumpet, flute, lute, harp, bagpipe, and all kinds of musical instruments], to fall down and worship the [oeb:statue|:image] which I have made, well[oeb: and good|:]; but if you do not worship, you [oeb:will|:shall] at once be thrown into a burning, fiery furnace. Where is there a god who can deliver you out of my hands?” \v 16 Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego replied, “O king, there is no need of our answering you about this. \v 17 Our God whom we serve is able to save us from the burning, fiery furnace; he will save us out of your hand, O king. \v 18 But if not, know, O king, that we will not serve your gods nor worship the golden image which you have set up.”

\p \v 19 Then Nebuchadnezzar was very angry and the appearance of his face changed, as he looked at Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego. He ordered that the furnace should be heated seven times hotter than usual. \v 20 He also commanded certain strong men who were in his army to bind Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, and throw them into the burning, fiery furnace. \v 21 Then these men were bound in their cloaks, their tunics, their robes, and their other garments, and were thrown into the burning, fiery furnace. \v 22 As the king’s command was urgent and the furnace very hot, the flames destroyed the men who took up Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego. \v 23 But Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, fell down, bound, into the midst of the burning, fiery furnace.

\p \v 24 Nebuchadnezzar, the king, was so astonished that he rose up hastily and said to his counsellors, “Did we not throw three men, bound, into the fire?” They answered, “True, O king.” \v 25 He said, “Now I see four men, unbound, walking in the midst of the fire, and they are unhurt, and the fourth looks like [oeb:a god|:an angel].”

\p \v 26 Then Nebuchadnezzar went near the door of the burning, fiery furnace and said, “Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, servants of the Most High God, come out.” Then Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego came out of the fire. \v 27 [oeb:T|:And t]he officers, governors, and counsellors who were there saw that the fire had no power over the bodies of these men, and that the hair of their heads was not singed and that their cloaks were not harmed, and that there was no smell of fire. And \v 28 Nebuchadnezzar said, “Blessed be the God of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, who has sent his angel to save his servants who trusted in him and refused to obey the king’s command and have offered their bodies, that they might not serve nor worship any god except their own. \v 29 Therefore I command that every people, nation, and [oeb:speaker of every language |:race ]that [oeb:|:shall ]say[oeb:s|:] anything against the God of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego [oeb:will|:shall] be cut in pieces and their house [oeb:will|:shall] be made [oeb:a ruin|:an ash-heap], for there is no other god who is so able to save as is this one.” \v 30 Then the king gave high positions, in the province of Babylon, to Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego.

\c 4 
\rem Student’s Old Testament
\s The king’s madness

\p \v 1 Nebuchadnezzar the king to all peoples, nations, and languages that [oeb:live throughout|:dwell in all] the earth: May your peace be great. \v 2 It [oeb:has|:hath] seemed good to me to show the signs and wonders that the Most High God [oeb:worked for|:hath wrought toward] me. \v 3 How great are his signs! And how mighty are his wonders! His kingdom is an everlasting kingdom, and his [oeb:rule|:dominion] [oeb:lasts|:is] from generation to generation. 

\p \v 4 I, Nebuchadnezzar, was at rest in my house, and prosperous in my palace. \v 5 I saw a dream that made me afraid; and the thoughts [oeb:on|:upon] my bed and the visions of my head troubled me. Therefore I made a decree to bring in all the wise men of Babylon before me, [oeb:so |:]that they might make known to me the interpretation of the dream. \v 7 Then the magicians, the enchanters, the Chaldeans, and the astrologers came in, and I told the dream [oeb:to|:before] them; but they did not make known to me its interpretation. 

\p \v 8 But at last there came before me Daniel, whose name was Belteshazzar, according to the name of my god, in whom is the spirit of the holy gods; and I told the dream [oeb:to|:before] him: \v 9 “[oeb:|:O ]Belteshazzar, chief of the magicians, because I know that the spirit of the holy gods is in you, and no secret troubles you, tell me the secret visions of my dream that I have seen, and its interpretation. \v 10 [oeb:These|:Thus] were the visions of my head [oeb:on|:upon] my bed: I saw[oeb:|:,] [oeb:|:and beheld, ]a tree in the midst of the earth, and its height was great. \v 11 The tree grew and was strong, and its height reached to heaven, and it could be seen to the end of the earth. \v 12 Its leaves were fair, and its fruit [oeb:abundant|:much], and in it was food for all; the [oeb:animals|:beasts] of the field found [oeb:shade|:shadow] under it, and the birds of the heavens [oeb:nested|:dwelt] in its branches, and [oeb:every kind of living being|:all flesh] was fed from it. \v 13 I saw in the visions of my head [oeb:on|:upon] my bed[oeb:|:, and behold,] a watcher, [oeb:|:even ]a holy one, came down from heaven. \v 14 He cried aloud, [oeb:|:and said, ]‘Hew down the tree, and cut off its branches, shake off its leaves, and scatter its fruit; let the [oeb:animals|:beasts] get away from under it, and the [oeb:birds|:fowls] from its branches. \v 15 But leave the stump of its roots in the earth, [oeb:|:even ]with a band of iron and [oeb:bronze|:brass]; [oeb:bound with iron and |:][oeb:bronze |:brass]he [oeb:will|:shall] be fed with the grass of the field, and wet with the dew of heaven, and his portion [oeb:will|:shall] be with the [oeb:animals|:beasts]. \v 16 His [oeb:mind|:heart] [oeb:will|:shall] be changed so that it [oeb:will|:shall] not be that of a man, and a[oeb:n|:] [oeb:animals’s|:beast’s] [oeb:mind|:heart] [oeb:will|:shall] be given to him, and seven times [oeb:will|:shall] pass over him. \v 17 The sentence is by the decree of the watchers, and the affair by the word of the holy ones, that the living may know that the Most High [oeb:rules|:ruleth] over [oeb:human|:the] kingdom[oeb:s|:] of [oeb:|:men and ][oeb:gives|:giveth] [oeb:them|:it] to who[oeb:|:mso]ever he will, and [oeb:can set |:setteth ]up [oeb:as ruler|:over it] the humblest of [oeb:people|:men]. \v 18 This dream I, King Nebuchadnezzar, have seen; and you, O Belteshazzar, [oeb:must |:]declare the interpretation, [oeb:since|:inasmuch ][oeb:|:as] all the wise men of my kingdom are not able to make known to me the interpretation; but you are able, for the spirit of the holy gods is in you.” 

\p \v 19 Then Daniel, whose name was Belteshazzar, was dumfounded for a moment, and his thoughts troubled him. The king [oeb:|:answered and] said, “Belteshazzar, let not the dream or the interpretation trouble you.” Belteshazzar answered [oeb:|:and said], “My lord, [oeb:I wish |:]the dream [oeb:applied|:be] to those who hate you, and its interpretation to your adversaries! \v 20 The tree which you saw, which grew and was strong, whose height reached to heaven, and the sight of it to all the earth, \v 21 whose leaves were fair, and whose fruit [oeb:abundant|:much], and in which was food for all; under which the [oeb:animals sheltered|:birds of the field dwelt], and upon whose branches the birds of the heavens had their [oeb:nests|:habitations], \v 22 is you, O king --- you who are great and strong; and your greatness has grown, and reaches to heaven, and your dominion to the end of the earth. \v 23 [oeb:You|:And whereas the king] saw a watcher, [oeb:|:even ]a holy one, coming down from heaven, and saying. Hew down the tree and destroy it. \v 24 This is the interpretation, O king, and it is the decree of the Most High, which has come upon my lord the king: \v 25 You [oeb:will|:shall] be driven from [oeb:people|:men], and your dwelling [oeb:will|:shall] be with the [oeb:animals|:beasts] of the field, and you [oeb:will|:shall] be made to eat grass as oxen, and [oeb:will|:shall] be wet with the dew of heaven, and seven times [oeb:will|:shall] pass over you; until you know that the Most High rule[oeb:s|:th] in [oeb:human|:the] kingdom[oeb:s|:] [oeb:|:of men] and give[oeb:s|:th] [oeb:them|:it] to whomever he will. \v 26 And [oeb:as|:whereas] they commanded to leave the stump of the roots of the tree, [oeb:so |:]your kingdom [oeb:will|:shall] be secure to you as soon as you recognize that the heavens do rule. \v 27 Therefore, O king, let my counsel be acceptable to you, and break off your sins by righteous works, and your iniquities by showing mercy to the poor; [oeb:then|: